In order to find information about the oxidation state of palladium in the catalyst, a solid UV spectrum of catalyst and PdCl2 as a source of Pd(II) species was studied (Fig. 2
                     ). Results indicated disappearing of a peak related to Pd(II) at 280 nm which confirms the reduction of Pd(II) to Pd(0).
                        18

XPS analysis confirmed the presence of carbon in the structure of Pd@CQD@Fe3O4 NPs with related peaks to C1s at 284.8 eV corresponding to CC, 286.4 eV for CO, and 288.6 eV for CO forms of carbon (Fig. 4
                     ).
                        20

Finally recycling of the Pd@CQD@Fe3O4 NPs was studied using the reaction of 4-bromobenzonitrile and phenylboronic acid under optimized reaction conditions. Results of this study by GC indicated that the catalyst recycled for 8 consecutive runs with 12% decrease in activity until run 8 and 27% decrease until run 9 (Fig. 8
                     ). It is worth mentioning that leaching of Pd after the 3 run was determined to be 2.3%, slightly higher than in the case of citric acid CQD.
                        14
